10.body: python and c It uses a rolling checksum algorithm (similar to rsync) to split large files into chunks. Bup can use "par2" redundancy to recover corrupted backups even if your disk has undetected bad sectors. https://blog.georgovassilis.com/2018/12/12/parchive-protecting-backups-against-data-corruption/ I think par2 is out (?), so have a look on erasure code. https://github.com/darrenldl/reed-solomon-erasure bup stores its data in a git-formatted repository. https://shafiul.github.io/gitbook/7_the_packfile.html git packs come in two parts: the pack itself (.pack) and the index (.idx). when generating a remote backup, we don't have to have a copy of the packfiles from the remote server the local end just downloads a copy of the server's index files, and compares objects against those when generating the new pack, which it sends directly to the server.
